  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">AUDIO VISUAL ARCHIVING FOR PEACE</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Two decades after the genocide, IRIBA Center plans to gather archives that cover more than a century of Rwandan audiovisual history; they will be collected through many sources.
Since 1994, all Rwandans now live with a heritage of genocide. Their efforts to reconstruct durable peace can no longer afford not to include a discovery or a rediscovery of their common history and their shared identity.
Iriba Centre, whose name means &#xAB; the source &#xBB; in Kinyarwanda, will gather together films, photographs, and audio documents dating from the beginning of the colonial period right up until today. At the site, in a building that the French Embassy in Kigali has made a commitment to put at our disposal, we will construct an educational desk with group programme sessions. IRIBA will equally organise mobile projections in rural areas where the majority of Rwandans live, notably paying attention to the most marginalised.
Audiovisual archives are an essential element of the cultural and historical heritage of any country, however, in Rwanda where few people read, and less than a generation after one of the worst genocides of the 20th century, these resources will be called upon to play a crucial role for future generations. Knowledge of the past will be essential forconstructing a future without conflict.
By consciously and deliberately making effort to educate Rwandan people especially the young, marginalized and in the rural areas about their culture, IRIBA has the advantage of reaching the unreachable. Being ableto take information to them using by sharing audio-visual archives also breaks barriers between the educated and those able to visit museums and pay fees to learn of the past.</narrative>
  </description>
